\begin_layout Section
Sphere bundles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point for this endevour is more-or-less an ordinary spin structure
 on flat Minkowski space-time.
 Details on how this is done can be found in Chapter 6 of Bleecker
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bleeker81"

\end_inset

.
 But first, some more hand-waving to paint the intuitive picture.
 A spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a point on the complex projective line, compactified
 as the Reimann sphere.
 In quantum mechanics, we normally expect to have our wave-functions to
 be normalized to unit-length.
 This can be acheived by delcaring them to be points in projective spaces,
 so that the unit-length normalization is a natural by-product of it being
 a projective space.
 A spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 has two complex components: it is the complex projective line 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}\left(\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 of all complex lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As a qubit, it is the same thing as the Bloch sphere, and is diffeomorphic
 to the 2-sphere.
 Wikipedia provides an adequate review of these relationships, and the different
 possible notations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make this work, start with a pair of 2-spinors, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\psi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, organized as a direct sum into a 4-spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\phi\oplus\bar{\psi}$
\end_inset

.
 These are understood to transform under the two-dimensional representations
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $sl_{2}\left(\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $sl_{2}\left(\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 is famously known two have a pair of complex-conjugate two-dimensional
 representations.
 These are famously homeomorphic to one of the connected components of the
 Lorentz group.
 This is obviously a fundamental cornerstone to the thesis presented here.
 Do not pass go, do not collect $200 if you don't know this inside-out and
 upside-down.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As usual, the bar denotes that the spinor transforms according to the conjugate
 representation.
 Denote the spaces which these spinors inhabit as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}=\mathbb{P}^{1}\left(\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbb{P}}$
\end_inset

, both being complex projective lines, but transforming under the conjugate
 representations.
 The spinors are just points in these two spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two bundles that suggest themselves.
 One is the trivial bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\left(\mathbb{P}\oplus\bar{\mathbb{P}}\right)$
\end_inset

 that is simply the Cartesian product of spaces, with 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 being Minkowski space.
 This can be understood as a space of Dirac-spinor-valued fields on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 The other is the trivial bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $TM=M\times\mathbb{R}^{4}$
\end_inset

 the tangent bundle on Minkowski space.
 These two can be made canonically isomorphic, in the usual sense.
 That is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{4}=\mathbb{P}\oplus\bar{\mathbb{P}}$
